# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 154-scottish-regiment-rlc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/10-queen-s-own-gurkha-logistic-regiment-rlc] The regiment was created on 5 April 2001.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/10-queen-s-own-gurkha-logistic-regiment-rlc] It was formed as a merger of The Queen's Own Gurkha Transport Regiment, The Gurkha Transport Regiment and The Gurkha Army Service Corps which formed as component parts of The Brigade of Gurkhas on 1 July 1958.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/10-queen-s-own-gurkha-logistic-regiment-rlc] A post on the Gurkha Brigade website in August 2016 noted that a further two new QOGLR squadrons will be formed in the future.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The regiment's history commences in the period immediately after World War II.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] At the time, the regional Commands HQs across the UK established Ammunition Inspectorates to oversee the drawdown of the vast stockpiles of ammunition in numerous sub depots across the country, much of it was still stocked alongside many of the roads in the countryside.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] These Command Ammunition Inspectorates, Northern Command, Southern Command etc. were eventually grouped into one unit, 1 Ammunition Inspection and Disposal Unit RAOC, which formed on 15 March 1972 at Salisbury.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] In April 1982, 1 Ammo IDU became 11 Ordnance Battalion (EOD) and was relocated to Didcot.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] On 5 April 1993, the battalion was retitled to 11 EOD Regiment RLC, following the formation of the RLC.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] In June 2018 the Regiment was renamed to 11 Explosive Ordnance Disposal and Search Regiment RLC, in recognition of the importance of Search within the Explosive Ordnance Disposal community.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The Regiment is based at Vauxhall Barracks, Didcot, Oxfordshire having moved there from Old Sarum in 1982.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] Due to its long and close association with the town, the Regiment was awarded the Freedom of Didcot on 17 September 2007 and were conferred "the honour and distinction of exercising all customary Regimental Privileges when parading in or marching through the Town of Didcot".
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The Regiment exercised its right to march through the town of Didcot on 22 September 2007, led by the Commanding Officer Lt Col RL Maybery QGM RLC.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] On 19 November 2010, in a ceremony at Didcot Parkway railway station, a High Speed Train locomotive, no.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] 43087 operated by Great Western Railway (FGW), was named *11 Explosive Ordnance Disposal Regiment Royal Logistic Corps*.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] The ceremony was attended by Lt Col Gareth Bex (Commanding Officer); soldiers of the Regiment; Mark Hopwood, of FGW; Keith Mitchell, leader of the county council; and the MP for Wantage, Ed Vaizey.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/11-explosive-ordnance-disposal-and-search-regiment-rlc] On 15 March 2018 the regiment was awarded the Firmin Sword of Peace, one of the highest accolades that can be bestowed upon a military unit.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/13-air-assault-support-regiment-rlc] The regiment was formed in 1999, upon the formation of 16 Air Assault Brigade, in order to provide logistical support to the brigade.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/13-air-assault-support-regiment-rlc] Elements of the regiment were deployed on Operation Herrick XX, the final phase of the UK’s combat operations in Afghanistan, that came to an end on 31 December 2014.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/13-air-assault-support-regiment-rlc] The regiment was deployed to Kabul on Operation Pitting, tasked to help evacuate British nationals and entitled Afghans as the Taliban took over Afghanistan in 2021.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/150-regiment-rlc] The regiment was formed in the Royal Corps of Transport in 1967, as **150th (Northumbrian) Transport Regiment** from seven territorial transport regiments, with four transport squadrons.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/150-regiment-rlc] The regiment was transferred into the Royal Logistic Corps and was renamed the **150th (Yorkshire) Regiment RLC** in 1993.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/150-regiment-rlc] 216 Squadron was transferred to 159th Support Regiment in 2006 but transferred back under Army 2020 in 2014.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/151-regiment-rlc] The parachute squadron was redesignated as a general transport squadron in 1978.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/151-regiment-rlc] The regiment was transferred into the Royal Logistic Corps in 1993, and 215 Squadron was disbanded.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/151-regiment-rlc] In 1999, the independent 124 Petroleum Squadron was absorbed.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/152-north-irish-regiment-rlc] The regiment was formed in the Royal Corps of Transport (RCT) in 1967 with two transport squadrons.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/152-north-irish-regiment-rlc] It was redesignated **152 (Ulster) Ambulance Regiment RCT** in the 1980s, and transferred into The Royal Logistic Corps (RLC) in 1993 as **152 (Ulster) Ambulance Regiment RLC**.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/152-north-irish-regiment-rlc] In 1999 it acquired a third squadron from 157 Transport Regiment and was put under the administrative control of the Army Medical Services.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/152-north-irish-regiment-rlc] In 2006 it re-roled as a transport regiment and was transferred back to control of The Royal Logistic Corps, returning an ambulance squadron to 157 Transport Regiment and acquiring a newly raised third transport squadron.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/152-north-irish-regiment-rlc] Under Army 2020 the regiment was paired with 9 Regiment RLC under 102nd Logistic Brigade, while the regiment joins 104th Logistic Support Brigade.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/152-north-irish-regiment-rlc] As part of this plan, the regiment became a specialist 'Fuel Support' regiment in 2015, the only unit of its type in the army.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/152-north-irish-regiment-rlc] The regiment also works closely with the Royal Engineers' 516 Specialist Team (Bulk Petroleum).
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/153-highland-transport-regiment] The regiment was formed from 433 (Forth) Regiment, Royal Corps of Transport in 1967.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/153-highland-transport-regiment] It consisted of three transport squadrons.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/153-highland-transport-regiment] A third transport squadron, 239 Squadron, was formed in 1969 taking many of the soldiers who had served in The Fife and Forfar Yeomanry/Scottish Horse when it was converted into a cadre in that year.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/153-highland-transport-regiment] Princess Alice visited the regiment in 1982.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/153-highland-transport-regiment] In 1992, 239 Squadron converted to re-form the Forfar Yeomanry/Scottish Horse Squadron of The Scottish Yeomanry.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/153-highland-transport-regiment] The regiment was amalgamated with 154 (Lowland) Transport Regiment in 1993 to form The Scottish Transport Regiment of the Royal Logistic Corps in 1993.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The regiment was formed as the **154th (Lowland) Regiment, RCT (Volunteers)** in Glasgow in 1967.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The initially comprised just 221 Squadron and 222 Squadron.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 527 Squadron, 230 Squadron and 231 Squadron and 251 Squadron were added on amalgamation with 153 (Highland) Transport Regiment to form the **Scottish Transport Regiment** in 1993.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 231 Squadron was subsequently disbanded.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] It became **154 (Scottish) Regiment RLC** under the Army 2020 reforms and an extra squadron, 239 Squadron, was formed in 2016.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The regiment wears the Tactical Recognition Flash of the Royal Logistic Corps.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] The tartan of the regiment is a version (designated "Government No.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] 16") of the main MacDuff tartan, but with a smaller green area, worn by unit's pipers and drummers; in regular uniform, it is only used for the diamond-shaped cockade backing the badge on the uniform cap.
[src:154-scottish-regiment-rlc/154-scottish-regiment-rlc] A tartan was created in 2018 (approved in 2020) in honour of the Royal Logistic Corps, but this is for civilian use and is a fundraiser for the RLC's MOD Benevolent fund; it is not used for regimental uniform.
